<section>
  <h1>Search</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    This form uses <code>method="GET"</code>, so everything you type is appended
    to the URL as a query string — it appears in the very first line of the
    HTTP request: <code>GET /search?q=…</code>.
  </p>

  <form class="lab-form" method="GET" action="/search">
    <label for="q">Search query</label>
    <input id="q" name="q" type="text" value="<%= q %>" placeholder="e.g. tcp handshake">

    <label for="secret">"Sensitive" field (don't use anything real)</label>
    <input id="secret" name="secret" type="text" value="<%= secret %>" placeholder="e.g. account-12345">

    <button type="submit">Search</button>
  </form>

  <% if (q || secret) { %>
    <p class="tip">
      Notice the address bar (and the captured <code>GET</code> line) now
      contains <code>q=<%= q %></code><%= secret ? ` &amp; secret=${secret}` : '' %>.
      A POST would have hidden these in the body — GET cannot.
    </p>
  <% } %>

  <% if (results.length) { %>
    <h2>Results</h2>
    <ul>
      <% results.forEach(function (r) { %><li><%= r %></li><% }); %>
    </ul>
  <% } %>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Capture this</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Display filter: <code>http.request.method == "GET" &amp;&amp; http.request.uri contains "/search"</code></li>
    <li>Look at the request line — the query string is right there in the URI, in cleartext.</li>
    <li>Lesson: URLs land in server logs, browser history, and proxies. GET is the wrong place for secrets.</li>
  </ul>
</section>
